commentBody:
@Brian 

I did.  And it was conscious. 

I'm not sure why, given the temper of these days, that DREAdSTATE is any more or less closed minded than DREAMSTATE.

@Steph

If the clue were simply "Boulevard", and the answer was STREET, would you have a problem?

I wouldn't.  So I think this is a perfectly reasonable clue.

@Elizabeth L

I did wonder if those particular ones would be challenging for other solvers. I figured I knew CERVEZA from high school Spanish class, but on second thought, I doubt they taught us that word. So I guess I knew it from drinking a lot of Corona "La cerveza mas fina" and Modelo Negra back in the day.  So I sussed ORE from the crosses.  I didn't know MOET was the first part of that company name, but really what other luxury company name starts with M and shows up in crosswords a lot? 

And somehow or other, JA RULE popped into my head (or it was in there already and rose to the surface) after a few crossing entries. So I got JAG from the crosses too. But if I hadn't known the rapper's name, I'd have had to run the alphabet at the end.

@Patrick J 

Well, there you go.  I knew a lot about the actual substance, but not the origin of the actual word.

Interesting the different facets there are to the interface between the solver and the puzzle.

@John 

Very true.  Very true.

As a former General Chemistry teacher, I tend to over-simplify.

@Andrzej, @David Connell

Lidl sounds like the kind of store I wish we had nearby. I love small, local grocers. Smart move not going with “Schwarz,” though. I learned from Mel Brooks that might carry a different meaning in Yiddish.

As for ALDI, I looked into it more and all 100+ locations in California are in the southern half of the state. So I reckon I’m not the only Northerner who’s never encountered one in the wild.

@Al  in Pittsburgh

@Al  in Pittsburgh

I definitely could be wrong. - I only know enough about Yiddish to know I admire its humor and creativity…

But, I grew up watching Spaceballs, and when Yogurt said “May the Schwartz be with you” my young mind made certain assumptions. 😂

@Andrzej
You and me both, my friend - Watched it on repeat on VHS.

@Caroline Kearney
I meant “Northerner” as in Northern California.

@Steve L 

I knew it would be ERA! Or at least I was 80% sure about it.

Soon I will not only be as Polish as żurek and as European as colonialism, but also as American as apple pie.

@Steve L 
Yes, got it! Somehow 'mound' was more familiar than 'diamond' and having 'stat' helped. 
You must be proud.

@Sam Lyons 

Oof! Not coffee with olive oil or butter, I hope! Those fats will leave grease stains that are hard to get out. 

Nice to see you back here.

@Eric Hougland

Hey, Eric! It’s always good to see you, too. 

You’re getting terrible ideas from crossword puzzles. I’m sure that oleato has its aficionados but, to me, it sounds like something that ought not to exist. Blecch…

@Sam Lyons 

The half-and-half we put in our coffee occasionally has lumps of butter in it. (I guess the roads are worse than they seem.) The slight greasiness isn’t bad, though I wouldn’t deliberately put butter in my coffee. 

The olive oil seems like a different thing. It’s got a more pronounced flavor (but I’m not a fan of olives themselves).

@Eric Hougland 

Hmm...hre's a puzzle for you- how does adding butter fat and coconut oil to a cup of joe make it bulletproof?

The idea of drinking that or even snorting it  - yikes. I'll just stick with champagne 🍾.

@Eric Hougland

I can eat pimiento-stuffed olives by the jar and at home we cook everything in olive oil. I’m actually quite the olive oil snob and have ours shipped directly from a producer in California. 

But keep it away from my coffee. It is a pronounced flavor, as you said, and I cannot imagine having it anywhere near my beans.

@Andrzej 
@Andrzej 
I took it as an adjective. "The speakers of Nahuatl were Aztec." Am I weird?

@LisaC 

Emus ate my first reply to you...

Thanks! I misread drip as drop, d'oh!

@Sonja

I held off on filling that one in because I thought the 4-letter answer could be either BOLT or REAR (up). 

The former seemed more typical, but I did experience firsthand a horse I was riding get spooked and rear up suddenly. I was about 12 years old in a lesson and it pretty much ended any interest I had in the sport, sadly. (The instructor didn't handle it well.)

@Devid I went down that hole for a bit, then realized the name was probably not a literal translation of red and sea, but the Latin name for the feature. Wiki says:

"The name Eritrea is derived from the ancient (originally Greek) name for the Red Sea, the Erythraean Sea (Ἐρυθρὰ Θάλασσα Erythra Thalassa, based on the adjective ἐρυθρός erythros "red")."

Maybe the Romans adopted the original Greek name? I'm sure someone will weigh in on this.

@Nora and @Devid 

I just realized that the clue implies the name is originally Latin. I suppose that when the Italians gave Eritrea its name, they could have been thinking of the Latinized name for the Red Sea, Mare Erythraeum, rather than its original name, but that doesn’t change the fact that the original etymology is Greek. 

Sorry for my previous post—sometimes I don’t read all the down clues when I’m solving mostly horizontally.

@Marks 

I always wondered what "reading between the lines" meant.

I think I get it now.

@Francis 

Aye. I only wiggled my way out of there with Google's help.

@Jane Wheelaghan

We should fist bump over knowing ERA 🤩

@Andrzej 
You're on!

After all, all things must pass.

@Andrzej 

Hey, didn't you see my reply the other night, giving you all the reasons why you don't need to put it off to 2029?

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/shared/comment/46n9bj?rsrc=cshare&smid=url-share" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/shared/comment/46n9bj?rsrc=cshare&smid=url-share</a>

@Jane Wheelaghan A “sub” is what we call hero (sandwich) in NYC. A finger sandwich is a small sandwich (sub-let).

A pinky ring is a tiny band (band-ito.)

The question mark at the end of the clue means it’s a play on words.

@Francis

Yeah, I saw it.

I thought I once told you not to despair! Seriously, I'm writing this from the capital of a country that suffered 8 years of horrific democratic backsliding between 2015 and 2023. In the end the people came together and restored reason and normalcy. The thing with autocrats in countries that have experienced true democracy is, they are never there to stay, because their policies simply don't work. If at least some democractic institutions remain, the people will use them to remove the autocrat. This mechanism worked even here in 2023, even though our democracy was only 30-ish years old then. Yours has been around for a quarter of a millenium! I have hope for you.

@Andrzej  and @Francis

I've copied your exchange and plan to share it.  

Thank you.

@Andrzej

Thanks for your insights.  I hope and believe that you are right.  

The irony of calling a group that tends to be oligarchic, autocratic, and xenophobic "populist" should not be ignored.

@Steve L 
Now I realise that there is some similarity with what we call a 'baguette' - a long thin crusty filled roll, but not usually with that much - Brie and cranberry or cheese and tomato or chicken and ham, but not all of them. No condiments - wouldn't that make it all soggy?!

There are Subway shops here, but I've never been inside. All the supermarkets and lots of small shops sell traditional sandwiches, in a triangular pack.

@Francis

The first time I visited the US, the bus took us on the New Jersey Turnpike. The poignant sting that came from seeing the sign still resonates.

Since that time I took many trips to look for America and I always found it somewhere. I think it's probably still there, but now I'd be afraid to go and look...

@Swift

This, 100%.


@Mike

I love that story! I was raised on Simon & Garfunkel (and then solo Simon). When I moved to NYC after college, my vision of the city was informed equally by his lyrics and Maurice Sendak's "In the Night Kitchen"... with the film The Warriors providing the counterpoint!

@Eric Hougland 

"...sometimes not looking at the clues."

Ye gods, and little fishes.

@Francis 

I think it was Vaer who termed this “Wheel of Fortune” solving. Maybe I’m just good at recognizing letter patterns, but I often get a couple of letters for a slot and know what the answer will be without reading the clue. I suspect that my familiarity with the words that show up repeatedly in crosswords helps out there. 

Skipping the clues is a good way to make easy puzzles more interesting. Someone in one of my Facebook groups claims to solve Monday NYT puzzles without looking at *any* clues. I’ve never gone that far, but I have filled in half or two-thirds of a Monday puzzle and then tried to finish without looking at the remaining clues.

@Eric Hougland 
I do call it that though I haven't trademarked marked it. :) I usually look at the clue to confirm that the answer makes sense however.

I thought LIL could have been clued as ___ Uzi Vert so we could have a rapper crossing a rapper, thus sparking rapper rage.

@G 

I guess I prefer it when I cotton to the theme in time for it to help me with difficult spots. Here, there were no difficult spots, which made it easier to ignore the theme. 

I hope you get your timer thing figured out. When I solve on our desktop computer, I sometimes see the timer running after I have finished the puzzle and gotten a gold star. But the stats page always seems to have the correct time.

@Rich in Atlanta 

HAIR, HEART and FINGER. 

Given the number of parts in a human body (or that of any animal with “fingers”), that seems like it’s not the tightest theme. But then there all food items, and I can’t immediately think of others.

@Xword Junkie 

Clearly "Submit" is also a "Button often pressed moments before noticing a typo."

disappointment

@haniblecter

I've never been to an apple orchard - or any orchard for that matter - where there was not an abundance of wasps. They thrive on the fallen fruit, don't they?

A single fruit tree is enough to attract wasps, let alone a whole orchard of them.

@G 

I wonder if that was part of the merger terms: “You get top billing in the full name and we get it in the stock market abbreviation.”

I don’t know, though, who selects the abbreviations used by the stock exchanges.

@Grant
No worries.  It was clear to me what you meant.
And I had to remind myself that X is not publicly traded.

@Vaer 

Thanks!

I assumed that it was mostly a decision made by the exchange. I’ve never been involved in an IPO and that’s fine with me. Just taking Business Associations in law school was enough.

@Hugh
How troublesome? Because "Mare Eritreum," or "Erythraeum," was *one* name in Latin for the Red Sea ("Mare Rubrum" was more common), it doesn't come from Latin word for "red" ("rubrum"), rather the Greek. But the Romans were, indeed, fond of adopting and adapting Greek words, especially when they wanted to sound fancy. It would be like saying the name in English was the Rouge Sea (and in fact, here in SE Michigan we have a watercourse named River Rouge.)

The linguistics of color terminology is a topic of great interest to me.

@Nitpicker

A logical, correct gripe about a small detail:
an ACU - NIT

@ClearThinker

